The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation
		 Monday, February 23, 2004 				 Curfew after Ujjain clash
																								Bhopal, Feb. 22 (Agencies): Authorities clamped curfew on Ujjain following clashes between two communities, police said today.																								Officials said two persons were hurt in the clashes that occurred late last night. Witnesses put the number at more than 50. 																								The clashes began after authorities demolished shops near a mosque to widen a road for the Simhastha 2004, a Kumbh mela.																								Inspector-general of police Sarabjeet Singh said the curfew was imposed to prevent a major flare-up. 																								The curfew will be relaxed from 7 am to 6 pm tomorrow.																								One officer said the police tried to disperse protesters near the mosque by using water cannons, batons and teargas. Suddenly, Hindus and Muslims started pelting stones at each other, he said.																								Municipal authorities had demolished the shops as they had been illegally constructed on government land, the officer added.																								No untoward incident has been reported from any part of the city since this morning. The situation is fully under control, collector Rajesh Rajora said.																								Superintendent of police Upendra Jain said 60 people, including five Simi activists, were held under preventive detention.
